A black box in your car?
While U.S. road planners find it difficult to find the money to repair the decrepitude of the highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself above your car's dashboard.
The aircraft, which records all the miles travelled by a motorist and transmits information to officials, is at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and the government planning offices to overhaul the obsolete system of financing the major American roads.
The generally uninterested sector of the planning of the main axes has suddenly provoked a very lively debate and heated alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups to press for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you are travelling, and possibly the road you are travelling on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is sore.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while Congressional members are unable to agree on whether to continue, several States have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move on to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental trip.
This is really essential for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which provides that the state will start recording the miles travelled by each Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with the taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to increase the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracers on 500 cars to test a payment system at the mile.
"It turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative," he said.
Wonks calls this a user charge for mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces the urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious laws on global warming.
But the representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chairman of the Transport Committee of the House of Representatives, said that he also considered it the most viable alternative in the long term.
Fans of the free market of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of charging drivers a mile.
"It's not just a tax rushing into a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment to the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are making progress.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometric charges instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is trying a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where approximately 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with an aircraft, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their every move.
"The concerns about Big Brother and this kind of thing are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management in Nevada's Transport Department.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full location devices."
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and goings.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact place and time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small start-up in California called True Mileage.
Originally, the company did not intend to assist motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It sought to break into the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have pleased the planners of the main axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Big mistakes have been made in pilot programmes in some States.
There are far less expensive means and much less intrusive methods of proceeding.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering different choices to motorists.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking costs, provide "driving payment" insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits of the system," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners are wondering whether the whole debate on payment in the mile is not simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing fuel taxes.
An additional one-off or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid vehicle drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, the director of legislation and public affairs at the commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listening
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
From The Next Day, released in January, he has produced a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new David Bowie album had left everyone pantois.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he had said that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last album, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few appearances in public, the English musician proved that he could still be relied on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke planned to re-release this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, new studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five specially unveiled songs for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and pouches, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new track Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and cleverly controlled rock electricity.
Unpublished ones already in tune
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a light cavalcade slows down gradually to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John's Rocket Man or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in any case in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie again refers to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The bewitching guitar riffs make you want to leave Earth.
Bowie has fun playing chameleon with these titles: turn-by-turn informant, man aboard a rocket, potential Martian...
He hides and reveals at the same time, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the L'Invitation au Voyage campaign, by the Louis Vuitton brand, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from 10 November.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that injured soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and noted that a transition process was followed by all soldiers prior to their return to civilian life.
Attacked by Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson assured that prior to their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All injured soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Critics accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured soldiers - who do not meet the "universal service" rule of the army requiring that staff be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by La Presse canadienne, including that of a soldier who was released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, with post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the army despite his request to stay another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case occurred after Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before being ready because he did not meet the universal service rule.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that it was totally different than wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse canadienne on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was any way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has been struggling to determine how much latitude it can give to injured soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not capable of fighting.
Under current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for overseas deployments, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the length of service required to obtain retirement benefits.
The Liberal spokesman for veterans, Jim Karygiannis, on Wednesday called for the reinstatement of Corporal Hawkins, while New Democrat Jack Harris called for the immediate end of "this shameful practice."
