Frontier Airlines plans to charge for hand baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 to passengers carrying hand baggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand baggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them on the descent of the aircraft.
The new hand luggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so the small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier stated that it would charge $25 if the charges were paid in advance and $100 if the passengers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier's spokesperson, Kate O'Malley, indicated that the $100 was planned to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to charge this price," she explained.
The airlines started charging the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these costs put as many things as they could in hand luggage in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in these compartments.
These charges are a means of ensuring that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said these new fees won't really be used to raise money.
The aim is to make the most loyal Frontier clients understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their ticket from the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger in queue at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag free of charge, while the next person in line might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand baggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Travellers often ruppet about baggage and other expenses, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people in Wall Street view the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Yet many of them did not pay for baggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand baggage charges three years ago, and low-cost Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the surcharge charges.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that Spirit's hand baggage costs were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he was going to find at the boarding gate when passengers discovered the company's unusual baggage charges.
"I had never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career," he said.
I expected to see a gnashing of teeth and a fight burst at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers boarded at the speed of lightning."
Frontier also acts as Spirit and charges $2 for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier has indicated that passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be re-worked free of charge.
It will always distribute water for free.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for the drinks in 2008 but returned seven months later after the passengers complained and no other major airline followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for carry-on baggage when passengers do not purchase their ticket directly from the airline is his final effort to encourage customers to go to his site.
