Republic tried to redress Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
The NSA is calling into question an "internal error" and not hackers for the failure of its site
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said on Friday that it was a bug that caused its public site to fail for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed on-line.
"NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update," said the spy agency in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service attack [DSD] are false.
Earlier this evening, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "not at all" compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the failure of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
The cyber-tactical is not very sophisticated and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The once ultra-secret NSA, a time nicknamed the "No Such Agency", has found itself in the spotlight and strongly criticized in recent months following a wave of revelations about its extensive national and international communications monitoring programs – which are part of the NSA's secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by the former disillusioned NSA consultant, Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has led to a lot of speculation that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
