Bombardier's profit in decline, as aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aviation and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in net profit on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and from contractual problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not provide flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide any information to determine whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September of this year.
After the first flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the aircraft flew only three times, and the question arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
Results were not up to forecast and stock prices fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst with the National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from "overperformance" to "sector performance" due to the low potential for stock market growth in the next quarter or two quarters.
"Although the drop in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed by the profit margin in the Transport division," Cameron Doerksen said in a note to customers.
We believe Bombardier will register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight testing program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family will be able to catapult it in the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft has so far been modest at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's claims regarding energy efficiency and the potential savings of the new airline.
Currently, the company has registered a total of 403 purchase orders and commitments from 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is confident that Bombardier will achieve its target of 300 firm orders before the first aircraft is put into commercial operation.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing according to schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," said Mr. Beaudoin at a conference call, adding that ground testing and software updates were planned during the aircraft's stopping time.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We had decided to proceed with a first flight and plan for an update period, and that is what we did.
This will occur throughout the flight schedule.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, while the others will follow shortly thereafter, the company said.
However, analysts are skeptical that the first client can fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its inaugural flight.
Bombardier indicated that it was in the process of evaluating the entry-into-service schedule and will provide new information in the coming months.
