Ukraine approaches bankruptcy
The credit rating agency Standard & Poor's lowered Ukraine's credit rating on Friday, questioning the ability of the former Soviet republic, which has been in recession for more than a year, to meet its financial obligations.
The rating of the country's public debt securities goes to "B-", falling into the category of speculative investments.
It is accompanied by a negative perspective, with S&P seeing at least one in three chances that it will be lowered again within a year.
"It is less and less likely that the government's strategy will guarantee enough foreign currency to meet its high external financing needs," says the US agency.
The Agency notes that Ukraine's foreign exchange reserves fell by 26% between September 2012 and September 2013 and expects the trend to continue.
This complicates the repayment of foreign credits.
These reserves, which the authorities rely heavily on to support the local currency, the hryvnia, falling, the agency finds increasingly likely a devaluation, which would inflate its external debt.
Kiev also needs liquidity to settle its gas imports to Russia, which accuses it of not paying an invoice of $882 million.
This announcement is bad news for the Ukrainian power in a period of intense tension with its Russian neighbour, furious about Kiev's willingness to sign an association agreement with the EU at the end of November.
It was made public the day after the publication of official statistics showing that the country's economy had experienced its fifth quarter of contraction between July and September.
Its debt, still relatively modest, has exploded in recent years and S&P estimates it at 33.5% of GDP, compared to less than 10% before the 2008-2009 crisis.
The country, with a budget deficit, has been seeking assistance from the International Monetary Fund for months, which granted it a credit of $15.3 billion in 2010 and has released only $3.4 billion for the time being.
But the Fund refuses to pay any new instalments until the country has adopted unpopular reforms to reduce its deficit, in particular by raising gas prices to the population.
Following a new unsuccessful mission to the country, the IMF noted this week that "important external financing needs" constituted "vulnerability", while noting "signs of economic improvement".
However, for economist Oleksandr Joloud of the Centre for Political Studies, "one cannot expect a short-term improvement".
"There is little hope that unpopular reforms will be launched in a pre-election year," the presidential elections being scheduled for 2015, notes the expert, interviewed at the AFP.
The only hope is an improvement in the international situation.
S&P also notes the "uncertainty" related to the possible signing of an association agreement between Ukraine and the EU, which Brussels conditions for the release of opponent Yulia Timoshenko.
"Singing the agreement would be positive for long-term trade but there could be negative short- and medium-term consequences related to Russia's reaction," S&P explained, who fears "trade restrictions" from Moscow.
