M23 officials explained that they had evacuated the localities under diplomatic pressure and Bertrand Bissimwa, the political leader of the rebellion, said on RFI that these military setbacks would not alter his demands at the peace talks.
The latter, according to Ugandan mediators, resumed on Wednesday in Kampala between the Kinshasa Government and the M23.
Squads are reported in the hills that dominate Bunagana, the last town in the hands of the insurgents to fall this week, and in the vicinity of Runyoni, a hill where the M23 rebellion began in 2012.
At their peak in November, the insurgents occupied Goma, the capital of North Kivu province, taking advantage of the flight of the government garrison and the passivity of the Monusco peacekeepers.
The fall of Goma has led the United Nations Mission in the DRC, the largest in the world in terms of personnel, to strengthen its mandate and to form a rapid intervention brigade composed of South African, Malawian and Tanzanian soldiers.
For its part, the FARDC staff has been redesigned and the army has moved on to the offensive against the M23, changing the course of the war.
The pace of progress of government troops is now unprecedented.
"The M23 seems to be coming to an end", predicts a Congolese affairs expert, Jason Stearns, on his blog Congo Siasa.
That would be historic - this would be the first time that the Kinshasa government has succeeded in defeating a major insurrection.
And it would also be the first time since 1996 that no armed group allied with Rwanda is present in the eastern DRC.
United Nations experts accuse Rwanda, which strongly denies it, of militarily supporting the M23, made up of mutiny former Congolese soldiers.
The head of British diplomacy, William Hague, invited Rwandan President Paul Kagame to exercise restraint, announced a spokesman for the Foreign Office.
Last week, Kigali referred to the possibility of military reprisals following the shells that had fallen in Rwandan territory.
On Wednesday, the inhabitants of Bunagana invaded the streets of the village to greet the entrance of FARDC soldiers.
"We lived a year with the M23 and it seemed unimaginable to us to be once liberated by the army," says a resident of this locality bordering Uganda.
"We have lived in terror (of the M23), we are traumatized," he added.
