For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of conflicts between government forces and the Renamo, the worst clashes since the peace agreement that was signed more than 20 years ago.
The Renamo was once a famous rebel movement, initially supported by the Rhodesia governed by whites and then the apartheid government of South Africa as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After a peace agreement signed in 1992, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country should not fall back into an open conflict, but recent events have shaken foreign investors and the local population.
The stakes are considerable for the growing economy as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale du Brazil, Eni d'Italie and Anadarko of the United States.
The Frelimo, the ruling party and the main political force since 1975, and the Renamo have mutually rejected the responsibility for tensions.
Renamo states that the government is behind the recent clashes and launched an attack on its members in Sofala province, a traditional Renamo bastion, on 17 October.
Attacks on former rebels then degenerated when government forces attacked the Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, and Fernando Mazanga, Renamo's spokesman, according to the Financial Times.
The government makes Renamo responsible for triggering the conflicts, and accuses her of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has sought to minimize concerns about instability.
