But the concern grew after Mr. Mazanga declared that the Renamo was abandoning the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the FT that he meant that the agreement was no longer respected by the Frelimo.
"We want to resume negotiations, but with the utmost seriousness," Mazanga said.
Previous discussions between the parties have failed to ease the tensions fuelled by a series of conflicts this year.
"It's two great men (Guebuza and Dhlakama) who keep arguing," explained Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the open university and specialist in Mozambique.
None of them knows how to negotiate well and none of them is prepared to make the necessary concessions.
The Renamo, which is in favour of electoral reforms, had already said that it would boycott the municipal elections to be held in November.
The presidential and legislative elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted its use of force as the attempt of a sick movement to obtain concessions and a war treasure from the government.
The share of votes won by the Renamo has been declining steadily since 1992, while a new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was created by a former member of the Renamo, is expected to win more votes in the elections.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Guebuza – who is expected to withdraw at the end of his second term next year – wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
"He doesn't want a multiparty democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace because he doesn't want to leave the presidency," Mazanga said.
We do not know exactly what the capacity of the Renamo is, but it has carried out disturbing flash attacks on police stations and vehicles on a major north-south motorway axis.
Most of the clashes took place in Sofala province, which is several hundred kilometres north of Maputo, but where Beira is located, the port from which mining companies, including Rio Tinto and Vale, export coal.
