NSA Espionage: the United States is "too far away", admits Kerry
The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in the field of espionage, acknowledged Secretary of State John Kerry, in this first Washington confession in full controversy with Europe on the massive collection of data by the National Security Agency (NSA).
After ten days of scandal, revelations and denials between the United States and its European allies, this is the first time that an American government official explicitly admits controversial practices in the NSA's interception of communications and data in Europe.
"In some cases, I agree with you, as the President did, some of these actions have gone too far and we will make sure that this does not happen again in the future," said John Kerry at a conference in London where he was participating from Washington on Thursday 31 October via video link.
In his retransmission, in the presence of his British counterpart William Hague, the head of American diplomacy has at length justified intelligence and information-gathering practices through the necessary fight against terrorism and the prevention of possible attacks.
Referring to the attacks of 11 September 2001, the attacks in Madrid in March 2004 and those in London in July 2005, John Kerry assured that the US authorities had since foiled many plans for attacks, through the interception of communications and the collection of information.
"We have effectively prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered, because we were able to be aware of these projects ahead," the boss of American diplomacy argued.
And, said John Kerry to the Europeans, "I assure you that innocent people have not been deceived in this process."
But we are trying to gather information.
"And yes, in some cases, it went too far inappropriately," admitted the Secretary of State, who had already had to speak about this international scandal during a tour last week in Paris, London and Rome.
On Thursday evening he assured that President Obama was "resolved to try to clarify and that he was conducting a review of these practices so that no one would feel deceived".
But the controversy between Americans and Europeans continued to swell this week with new revelations in the press.
According to the Washington Post, the NSA intercepted data from hundreds of millions of Google and Yahoo users.
The newspaper, which cites documents obtained from the former NSA consultant Edward Snowden, states that the program called "MUSCULAR" and conducted with the British NSA homologue, the GHQ, allows these two agencies to recover data from optical fibers used by Internet giants.
According to one of the documents, some 181 million items had been collected in January alone - ranging from metadata on e-mails, text elements or audio or video documents.
These interceptions would take place outside the United States.
But Yahoo and Google have denied any connection to these practices.
Over the past ten days, several major newspapers in France, Germany, Spain or Italy have revealed that the NSA has intercepted massively data and communications from allies of the United States and their leaders, including German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Faced with the anger of European states and while leaks in the American press claimed that the US President was not aware of such listenings, Barack Obama refused to speak on this subject, citing national security.
On the other hand, the boss of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied that his intelligence agency had captured tens of millions of communications from European citizens.
He even sent the bullet back to the European intelligence services, which allegedly seized these communications, before providing them to the NSA.
This would involve "military operations" in countries where NATO's allies cooperate with the United States and would not be aimed at Europe at all," said General Alexander.
And the controversy extended to Asia on Friday.
Indonesia has summoned the Australian Ambassador, whose mission is accused of being used by the Americans as part of an extensive international spying network that has also sparked China's anger.
