Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Does a mother have to worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr.Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring the parents – in general, this does not indicate a rapid evolution towards full puberty," said Kaplowitz.
The obvious signs of development, such as breast budding, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the first rules over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age was 12 and a half years, compared to 12 years three quarters in 1970.
"Once the chest has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first rules appear," said Kaplowitz, also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test to know how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual appearance of puberty, but it is considered "early" when the development of the chest is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something that a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster evolution may justify testing by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumours or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of bones that can hinder growth and small size in adulthood.
The recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on the age of the child, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is careful with drugs but recognizes that "controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioural problems and the feeling for girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young girls to have their menstruation.
"They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will manage hygiene issues," said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at the age of 10.
Even if there were signs and we had talked about the rules, it was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public's attention about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual media messages are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz states that the most credible hypothesis is the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls between the ages of 6 and 9 that links the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything, from economic conditions to climate, through genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their faces and in the younger pubic area, the trend towards true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true appearance of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a paediatric endocrinologist working at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected," said Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls with early puberty must be reassured that, even when this happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
