Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies have shown that happy dogs move their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs move more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that as in humans, the right side of the brain in dogs was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disorderly tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We have presented to dogs films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we have been able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog with no expression moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail that deviated mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement from their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at Bristol University's School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs were turning their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs were easier to go to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements from different mammals indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
