A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin?
It's good news, but I'm not surprised.
While in the past species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographic basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
It is not impossible, moreover, that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged due to advances in genetics.
Similarly, two very morphologically close species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has stated?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if there is a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture in the region, we could be dealing with extinction of a species, rather than local extinction of a population of a species that is more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the potential for recovery from neighbouring stocks.
For the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new discovered species has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems favour genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known.
We'd rather send robots to Mars than know what lives in the Mariana pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money in the search for life on other planets than in marine research and it is high time that this change.
