This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma whose sequelae he was going to carry the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years with his father in crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could get.
"It's not easy," Bwelle adds.
You can leave the house at 5:00 a.m., run into the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There's a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
By comparison, the U.S. ratio is 1 physician per 413 population.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of the country's health expenditure is in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," said Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and as many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed more than 700 surgical procedures free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they choke in vans after fixing the medical equipment on the roof and crossing difficult terrain to reach the villages most in need of assistance.
Chance doesn't always follow them.
They had to push the vehicles many times to cross muddy rivers or tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr.Bwelle – with his big smile and overflowing energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team began to receive hundreds of patients.
"We get 500 people on each visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this mobile hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a pair of glasses collected or a free birth certificate – a document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical acts under local anaesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, town hall or house; after the procedure, the patient gets up and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a gruelling rhythm, but the musicians in the villages usually help the team stay motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working," said Mr. Bwelle.
On Sundays, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgical acts free of charge over the last year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," the man said.
In addition to living this mobile hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr.Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's asleep," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student from Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteered with Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is a field learning opportunity they don't have at home.
"We were able to participate in operations to help with the blood or to pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
It's not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you're a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay for their journey to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their boarding, transportation and teaching are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to extinction.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happily by keeping his promise to his father is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," said Mr. Bwelle.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons that make me do that.
