John Kerry admitted, unprecedented fact, that American espionage "had gone too far inappropriately"
John Kerry indicated a softening of the defensive attitude of the United States towards its surveillance programs by admitting, made unprecedented, that on several occasions, espionage "had gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on "autopilot" when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA's spying activities came into being.
The leaks put the US government at the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned some things in automatic pilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 11 September."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that American espionage had gone beyond limits, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said, "In some cases, it went too far inappropriately."
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Mr. Kerry stressed, however, that the NSA was an active force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: "We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up."
There is radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
