"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay with us in the mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chair of the US Senate's European Affairs Sub-Committee, in an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to combat terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some US allies, but the director of the agency said this week that it was incorrect and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations referred to documents disclosed by Snowden according to which the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the allied espionage by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of tumult, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating legislators should be revealed in the coming days.
